The article provides an overview of the United States' response to the Haiti earthquake disaster in 2010. The government launched a whole-of-government effort involving over 20,000 civilian and military personnel to support the people of Haiti. The response included search and rescue operations, restoring airports and seaports, providing medical services, and addressing basic needs such as food, water, and shelter. The US military and Coast Guard played a significant role in these efforts. Additionally, coordination and communication with various agencies and organizations, including the Government of Haiti and non-governmental agencies, were prioritized. The article also highlights the provision of relief programs to benefit the local Haitian economy, such as cash-for-work programs. Evacuation of US citizens and repatriation of remains were also carried out.